                        "content": "The nurse is caring for a client diagnosed with a hepatitis D virus (HDV) infection. Which laboratory test result would the nurse anticipate that is associated with this infection?",
                        "subjectId": "ad5ab04c79144c0ea9b83385308c3b1d",
                        "difficultyIds": "11797937e327eb6d913faa80427c566b",
                        "difficulty": "考试范围-Analyzing 分析",
                        "textAnalysis": "Rationale:\nHepatitis refers to inflammation of the liver that is most often caused by a viral infection, but can be caused by various substances, such as alcohol, medications, chemical exposure, or autoimmune conditions. There are various types of hepatitis virus, including hepatitis A, hepatitis B, hepatitis C, hepatitis D, and hepatitis E. Hepatitis D is unique in that it can only cause an infection if the host is co-infected with hepatitis B, as it requires hepatitis B surface antigen to serve as its outer viral shell. Therefore, the correct answer is the laboratory result that indicates to the nurse that the client has a hepatitis B infection. Eliminate option 2 because this indicates that the client does not have the hepatitis B surface antigen present, which is positive during chronic hepatitis B infection. Eliminate option 3 because a normal ALT ranges from 4 to 36 U/L, and the nurse would expect the value to be elevated in the client with hepatitis. Next, eliminate option 4 because this indicates the client has not been exposed to hepatitis B and does not have immunity against hepatitis B. Therefore, option 1 is correct.",
                        "id": "96ed3fff75a347e092285aa7f5acc327",
                        "mark": "0",
                        "collectionState": "0"
                    },
